{"key":"processedPost-6879830","value":{"id":6879830,"first":6613734,"last":17821829,"when":1178466957,"utime":"05/06/07 06:55 PM","content":"Most of them were posted in the edible forum.  To my surprise, lion's mane did better on brf/verm than on brf/sawdust.  Oysters didn't seem to mind one way or the other and fruited well on both.  Shiitake would only fruit on the brf/sawdust.  I left shiitake in the jars because I've found they like to pin at the edge of the substrate.  I usually also leave part of the spawn bag in place until pinning starts when I grow shiitake in filter patch bags. In this case I left them in the jars to conserve moisture because shiitake are generally slower growing than what usually is put on pf cakes. I was unable to get P. nameko to fruit on cakes at all, nor was I able to get anywhere with several species of agaricus.<br /><br />In all cases, rice bran was superior to brown rice flour.  I used it in the same quantities as brf, but brans have the outer shell still in place when ground, so apparently the mycelium appreciates the extra food.<br />RR<br /><br /><a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-14/575068320-Shiitake_on_pf_tek_a5a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-14/575068320-thumb_Shiitake_on_pf_tek_a5a.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-14/575068291-Shiitake_on_pf_tek_7a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-14/575068291-thumb_Shiitake_on_pf_tek_7a.jpg\"></a> <a href=\"https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-14/575087590-Shiitake_on_pf_tek8a.jpg\" class=\"highslide\" onclick=\"return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})\" target=\"_blank\"><img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"/forums/thumbs/07-14/575087590-thumb_Shiitake_on_pf